Mortality Analysis for 2016: Models and Tests

Tamara Cooper

Purpose and Goals

The purpose of this code is to perform various statistical analyses on the mortality data in the nc2016.csv data set that I prepared in the data aggregation project. (Please see the 2016Mort_dataAggr.html and 2016Mort_explorAna.html files to view the data aggregation and exploratory analysis projects.)
My goals for this project are to check independence and variance, perform regression analyses, and test for any interaction effects. I will also check the data for spatial dependence and perform a spatial regression analysis if spatial dependence is found.

Multiple Linear Regression Model

From the exploratory analysis performed in the 2016Mort_explorAna.html file I decided to perform the regression analysis on the following variables:

ageAdjRate - the age adjusted mortality rate for NC 2016, dependent variable

Independent variables:
mentUnhDays - poor mental health days
perAccToExer - percent with access to exercise opportunities
perExcDrink - percent excessive drinking
perUnemploy - unemployment Rate
perChlamyd - percent Chlamydia cases
tBirthRate - teen births rate
vioCrimeRate - violent crime rate
perInsSleep - percent insufficient sleep

Model 1

From the model we see that the perAccToExer and tBirthRate variables are significant at the α = 0.05 and α = 0.001 levels, respectively. We also see that the vioCrimeRate variable is significant at the α = 0.1 level. Next I will perform some residual diagnostics to check that the model doesn’t violate the normality, linearity, and homoscedasticity assumptions.

Model 1 - Residual Diagnostics
mod_res <- mod$residuals

# Histogram of residuals
hist(mod_res, main = "Histogram of Residuals", col = "cyan", xlab="Residuals")

# Normal Q-Q plot
qqnorm(mod_res)
qqline(mod_res, col = "magenta", lwd = 2)

# Residuals vs. fitted values
plot(fitted(mod), mod_res, title("Residual vs. Fitted Values"), xlab="Fitted Values", ylab="Residuals", col="blue")
abline(0, 0, col="darkorange", lwd = 2)


From the histogram of the model residuals we see that the residuals follow a normal distribution and the normality assumption is not violated.
The Normal Q-Q Plot shows us that the data are normally distributed and thus the normality assumption is not violated.
And from the plot of the residuals vs. the fitted values we see that the residuals are randomly distributed around the 0 line, showing us that the relationship is linear. We see homogeneity of error variance since the residuals form an approximately horizontal band about the 0 line, thus the homoscedasticity assumption is not violated. Finally, we see the possibility of a couple of outliers at y = 2 and y = -2 but since they are not extremely far from the random pattern we may only take note of them at this time.

lw <- nb2listw(nb, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)  ### assign weights


Create a scatter plot between age adjusted mortality rate values and their lagged counterparts

Just for fun here’s a scatter plot of the rate values with the lagged values

mort_lag <- lag.listw(lw, shapeFile$ageAdjRate)
# mort_lag   ### Lagged values

plot(mort_lag ~ shapeFile$ageAdjRate)

abline(mort_line, col="#5A01B3")


Compute the slope of the line
### compute the slope of the line which is the Moran's I coefficient
coef(mort_line)[2]
## shapeFile$ageAdjRate 
##               0.1781


The computed slope of the model is the Moran’s I coefficient.

Compute the Moran’s I statistic
### compute Moran's I statistic
mI_stat <- moran(shapeFile$ageAdjRate, lw, length(nb), Szero(lw))[1]
mI_stat
## $I
## [1] 0.1781


Note that the Moran’s I statistic is equal to the computed slope of the model.

Moran’s I hypothesis test

We will test the following hypothesis:
H_0: The age adjusted mortality rate values are randomly distributed across counties following a completely random process.
H_1: The age adjusted mortality rate values are not randomly distributed across counties.

We will test this at the α = 0.05 level.

Moran’s I test - Analytical Method
### Moran's I hypothesis test
moran.test(shapeFile$ageAdjRate, lw, alternative = "greater")
## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  shapeFile$ageAdjRate  
## weights: lw    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 2.9, p-value = 0.002
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##          0.178150         -0.010101          0.004257


We see that the p-value = 0.002 < α = 0.05 so we reject the null hypothesis and concluded that there is spatial dependence.
The analytical method may be sensitive to irregularly distributed polygons and a safer method is the Monte Carlo simulation seen below.

Moran’s I test - Monte Carlo Method
### Moran's I hypothesis test using the Monte Carlo method
mc <- moran.mc(shapeFile$ageAdjRate, lw, nsim = 9999, alternative = "greater")
mc
## 
##  Monte-Carlo simulation of Moran I
## 
## data:  shapeFile$ageAdjRate 
## weights: lw  
## number of simulations + 1: 10000 
## 
## statistic = 0.18, observed rank = 9971, p-value = 0.003
## alternative hypothesis: greater


With the Monte Carlo approach we see that the p-value = 0.003 < α = 0.05 so we reject the null hypothesis and concluded that there is spatial dependence.

Plot the Density of Permutation Outcomes

### density plot of the null distribution
plot(mc)


In the density plot of permutation outcomes is a graphical representation of the Monte Carlo method. The curve shows the distribution of Moran I values we could expect if the age adjusted mortality rate were randomly distributed across the counties. Note that the observed statistic, 0.1781, falls in the right tail of the distribution suggesting that the mortality rate values are clustered. A negative Moran’s I value would suggest dispersion.

Map the 2016 Age Adjusted Mortality Rate

nc_shp <- read_sf("./SpatialData/nc_mort16_spat.shp")

The Lagrange multiplier tests are another way to determine if there is spatial dependence. From the p-value results of the above tests we see that only in the case of LMerr do we reject the null hypothesis at α = 0.05 and so we should use a spatial error model.

I will run four spatial regression models to demonstrate them but note that the above Lagrange multiplier test only found that our model could be improved with a spatial error model, SEM model.

The SLX Spatially Lagged X model, y = Xβ + WXθ + ε, includes the average values of neighboring counties’ percent access to exercise, teen birth rate, violent crime rate, teen birth rate and violent crime rate interaction. This is a Local Spatial Model.
We see with this model that perAccToEx and tBirthRate are significant variables at the α = 0.01 and α = 0.05 levels, respectively.
Compared to the OLS Model 4, ageAdjRate = perAccToExer + tBirthRate + vioCrimeRate + tBirthRate*vioCrimeRate, we see that the Intercept, perAccToEx, and tBirthRate are significant at the same level in both models but the adjusted R-squared of the OLS Model 4 is slightly better at 0.496.
The impacts(.) function shows us the total affects, where in the SLX model we see the direct affect from the X values and the indirect affect from the lagged X values. From the p-values printed out from the impacts(.) function we see that the total affects are not significant.

In the SAR model, y = ρWy + Xβ + ε, spatially lagged y values are included, meaning that values of age adjusted mortality rates of neighboring counties are included in the model. This is a Global Spatial Model.
We see with this model that perAccToEx and tBirthRate are significant variables at the α = 0.05 level. The p-value for Rho, the spatially lagged y multiplier, is 0.10597 and is not significant at the α = 0.05 level.
Compared to the OLS Model 4 we see that the perAccToEx is not quite as significant in the SAR model.
In order to run the impacts(.) function for this model I needed the spatial data without NA’s so I created the spatial data files in QGIS using the nc2016_noNA.csv file. From the p-values printed out from the impacts(.) function we see that the total affects for tBirthRate are significant at the α = 0.01 level and the total affects for perAccToEx are significant at the α = 0.1 level.

In the SEM model, y = Xβ + u with u = λu + ε, a residual (unexplained) value is included in the model. This is a Global Spatial Model.
We see with this model that perAccToEx and tBirthRate are significant variables at the α = 0.01 level.
The Lambda value is the coefficient for the spatial error term, it reflects unobserved similarities in neighboring counties, here the p-value for Lambda is 0.026 < 0.05 and thus is significant at the α = 0.05 level.
Compared to the OLS Model 4 we see that the tBirthRate is more significant in the SEM model.

Spatial Hausman Test

We will test the following hypothesis:
H_0: There is no difference in the values generated from the two models (OLS and SEM).
H_1: There is a difference in the values generated from the two models (OLS and SEM).

We will test this at the α = 0.05 level.

Hausman.test(mod_spat)
## 
##  Spatial Hausman test (asymptotic)
## 
## data:  NULL
## Hausman test = 5.6, df = 5, p-value = 0.3


p-value is greater than α = 0.05 so we fail to reject the null hypothesis and we conclude that the spatial error model may be appropriate.
Note: While performing multiple runs of this test I got p-value = 0.3 and p-value = 1. A p-value = 1 is suspicious and leads me to believe that something has gone wrong in this test, but since this is only a fun project displaying various methods I will not dig further into this concern at this time.

The Spatial Durbin Error Model, y = Xβ + WXθ + u where u = λWu + ε, is the Spatial Error Model (SEM) with lagged X values.
We see with this model that perAccToEx and tBirthRate are significant variables at the α = 0.01 and α = 0.05 levels, respectively.
The p-value for Lambda is approximately 0.05 < 0.1 and thus is significant at the α = 0.1 level.

Conclusion

From the above analysis we found a statistically significant negative relationship between the age adjusted mortality rate and access to exercise and a statistically significant positive relationship between age adjusted mortality rate and teen birth rates in North Carolina in the year 2016.
